As with Zamoyskiana, the issue here is the parentage is difficult to determine from trichome examination. It is most likely a hybird between either T. americana var. americana and T. americana var. heterophylla, or T. americana and T. tomentosa. "moltkei" when used as a nothospecies also has priority issues with "viridis". For this reason, I would ignore the nothospecies and just call this T. 'Moltkei' for the time being

column5:
valid nothospecies for T. cordata x dasystyla, though its parentage has been debated based on ploidy level. This name refers to a largely clonal cultivated form which might be either better as Tilia 'Euchlora' or Tilia xeuchlora 'Euchlora' depending on what the parentage looks like. Updated and comment from 7/29/2020: ML: Tilia ×euchlora 'Euchlora' for the following reasons:
1- euchlora is a valid nothospecies for cordata and dasystyla (latin description, etc.)
2- there is at least one other cultivar for the hybrid ('Laurelhurst')
3- we need to be able to distinguish between the clonal "Euchlora" (i.e. the old cultivar) and the nothospecies "euchlora" which could be applied to any cordata × dasystyla seedling.

We may need to revisit this if we start to suspect that euchlora is not actually a cordata×dasystyla hybrid, or if we start to think dasystyla = platyphyllos, but in either case 'Euchlora' would remain the cultivar epithet, only the (notho)species would change

I would continue to treat this as a species, though the taxonomy of this is still debated. See New Trees (Grimshaw/Bayton) "The exact status of the Kirghiz Apple is debated. Fiala (1994) treated it as a crabapple cultivar (Malus <d4>Kirghisorum<d5>). Dzhangaliev et al. (2003) maintain it as a full species, while Juniper & Mabberley (2006) regard it as a distinct species occurring sympatrically with M. pumila in the Tian Shan, and intermediate between it and M. baccata in characters." You may be able to red list this if it appears to be a distinct "entity" (regardless of which rank it sits at), but I wouldn't consider this a big priority

column5: I would not bother red-listing this. This is a species Pigott named off a voucher of a Hers collection which originated from the hills around the Anhui/Jiangsu border. There are some morphological differences between this and some of the T. oliveri types which occur around there (and it is also a tetraploid) whichprobably merits some investigation, but with only two known individuals, this is probably a taxonomic question prior to being a conservation question.

Flora of china lists four varieties based predominantly on fruit morphology. I think most of these were from the Korean peninsula. Pigott seemed doubtful this was valid. I don't think it's helpful to have four lower taxa for the sake of this project, so please just red list this as one species.
Flora of China lists a "var. cinerascens", but Pigott argues those specimens are generally misidentified and should be T. chingiana
